From e933e6e5d5035f5f7c0cf78f93ffa94de0c1b564 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Claude <claude@anthropic.com>
Date: Fri, 17 Jul 2026 01:32:17 +0000
Subject: [PATCH 2/2] Make the application name editable (white-label
 groundwork)

First piece of "could this be sold to another manufacturer" - the app
name was hardcoded as "HVACFlow" in 5 places (login logo, sidebar logo
x2, browser tab title default/template). Now backed by a real setting.

New OrganizationSettings model - a singleton row (always id="default"),
one per deployment. Deliberately NOT a multi-tenant table with an
organizationId - per this session's earlier discussion, Option C is
one separate deployment per customer, not shared tenant infrastructure,
so a single settings row per install is the right shape, not
over-engineering toward B.

GET /organization-settings is @Public() - the login page needs the
name before any JWT exists. It only ever reveals the display name,
nothing sensitive. PATCH requires config:manage.

New Configuration -> General page to edit it. Login page and both
sidebar logo spots now read this instead of a hardcoded string; the
browser tab title updates client-side via document.title once the
name loads (the root layout's static <title> is a build-time default
Next.js can't easily make dynamic without a server-side fetch - a
brief generic flash before hydration is normal/expected for this
pattern, same as most SPA-style apps).

Deliberately did NOT touch seed.ts for this - the migration creates
the initial row once, and the service's get() upserts with an empty
update (never overwrites an existing name). Adding seed logic here
would risk silently resetting a customer's chosen name back to
"HVACFlow" every time db:seed re-runs, which happens routinely in this
project's normal workflow.
